name: hdc_training_validation
version: "1.0.0"
language: zig
module: hdc_training_validation

description: |
  HDC Training Validation — Level 10A.11: Empirical Convergence on Real Corpus.
  Trains the ternary transformer on inline Shakespeare text and records
  actual loss curves, perplexity measurements, and convergence behavior.

  === THE GAP THIS CLOSES ===
  v2.24 specified convergence_monitor with 6 anomaly types and 4 LR schedules.
  v2.25 specified convergence_zero with curriculum learning and convergence guarantee.
  NEITHER has been validated with actual training on real text.
  This spec bridges theory → empirical measurement.

  === TRAINING PROTOCOL ===

  Corpus: Inline Shakespeare (1,024 chars, ~70 unique chars)
  Tokenization: Character-level (each char = 1 token)
  Dimension: D=256
  Context: 8 tokens → predict next
  Samples: ~1,016 (context, target) pairs
  Split: 80% train (812), 10% eval (102), 10% test (102)

  === NO-BACKPROP TRAINING (3-op update) ===

  For each sample (context, target):
    1. Forward pass (as specified in execution_proof):
       output_hv = forward(context)
       predicted = codebook.decode(output_hv)

    2. Compute error:
       target_hv = codebook.encode(target)
       output_neg = vsa.bind(output_hv, NEGATE_HV)  // element-wise negate
       error_hv = vsa.bundle2(target_hv, output_neg) // direction toward target

    3. Sparsify (learning rate as sparsity):
       sparse_error = sparsify(error_hv, lr)
       // Zero out (1 - lr) fraction of trits
       // lr=0.1 → keep 10% of error trits → gentle update
       // lr=0.3 → keep 30% → aggressive update

    4. Update roles:
       For each role r in {Q, K, V per head, FF1, FF2}:
         role[r] = vsa.bundle2(role[r], sparse_error) // 2,387 ns per role
       11 roles * 2,387 ns = 26,257 ns ≈ 26 us per update

    Per-sample cost: ~286 us (forward) + 26 us (update) = ~312 us
    Per-epoch (812 samples): ~253 ms
    10 epochs: ~2.5 seconds total

  === CONVERGENCE EXPECTATIONS ===

  Based on Kanerva theory for D=256:
    Epoch  1: loss ~0.85, PPL ~65 (near-random)
    Epoch  3: loss ~0.60, PPL ~45 (learning character frequencies)
    Epoch  5: loss ~0.45, PPL ~30 (learning common bigrams)
    Epoch  8: loss ~0.30, PPL ~20 (learning local patterns)
    Epoch 10: loss ~0.25, PPL ~18 (near convergence)
    Epoch 15: loss ~0.20, PPL ~15 (diminishing returns)

  Convergence criterion: eval_loss < 0.3 (v2.25 guarantee)
  Expected samples needed: max(16 * 70, 500) = 1,120
  At 812 train samples/epoch: ~1.4 epochs to threshold
  Conservative: 5 epochs to account for ternary quantization noise

  === LEARNING RATE SCHEDULE ===

  Phase 1 (epoch 1-3):   lr = 0.20 (aggressive, establish patterns)
  Phase 2 (epoch 4-6):   lr = 0.10 (moderate, refine)
  Phase 3 (epoch 7-10):  lr = 0.05 (gentle, fine-tune)
  Phase 4 (epoch 11-15): lr = 0.02 (minimal, polish)

  === WHAT THIS PROVES ===
  1. No-backprop training (bind + negate + sparsify + bundle2) causes loss to DECREASE.
  2. Perplexity drops from baseline (~70, random over vocab) to < 30.
  3. The convergence guarantee (eval_loss < 0.3) is achievable within predicted samples.
  4. Role vectors accumulate meaningful structure (not random noise).
  5. Training is fast: < 3 seconds for 10 epochs on 1K corpus.

  Trinity Identity: phi^2 + 1/phi^2 = 3
  Sacred Formula: V = n * 3^k * pi^m * phi^p * e^q

types:
  TrainingSample:
    fields:
      context_tokens: List<String>
      target_token: String
      sample_id: usize

  EpochResult:
    fields:
      epoch: usize
      train_loss: Float
      eval_loss: Float
      train_perplexity: Float
      eval_perplexity: Float
      train_accuracy: Float
      eval_accuracy: Float
      learning_rate: Float
      role_drift: Float
      epoch_time_ms: Float
      samples_processed: usize

  LossCurve:
    fields:
      epochs: List<usize>
      train_losses: List<Float>
      eval_losses: List<Float>
      train_perplexities: List<Float>
      eval_perplexities: List<Float>

  ConvergenceResult:
    fields:
      converged: Bool
      convergence_epoch: usize
      convergence_samples: usize
      final_train_loss: Float
      final_eval_loss: Float
      final_test_loss: Float
      final_test_perplexity: Float
      final_test_accuracy: Float
      guarantee_met: Bool
      predicted_samples: usize
      actual_samples: usize

  RoleDriftAnalysis:
    fields:
      role_name: String
      initial_density: Float
      final_density: Float
      total_drift: Float
      drift_per_epoch: List<Float>
      is_alive: Bool

  AnomalyLog:
    fields:
      epoch: usize
      anomaly_type: String
      severity: String
      description: String
      auto_fixed: Bool

  TrainingValidation:
    fields:
      loss_curve: LossCurve
      convergence: ConvergenceResult
      role_analysis: List<RoleDriftAnalysis>
      anomalies: List<AnomalyLog>
      total_training_time_ms: Float
      total_epochs_run: usize
      early_stopped: Bool

behaviors:
  - name: initTrainingValidation
    given: D=256, H=3, inline Shakespeare corpus (1,024 chars)
    when: Build codebook, init roles, tokenize, split 80/10/10, create samples
    then: Training validation engine ready with real data

  - name: computeError
    given: Output HV from forward pass and target token
    when: |
      target_hv = codebook.encode(target)
      neg_output = elementwise_negate(output_hv)  // flip all trits
      error_hv = vsa.bundle2(target_hv, neg_output)
    then: Error HV pointing from output toward target in HD space

  - name: sparsifyError
    given: Error HV and learning rate (0.0 to 1.0)
    when: |
      For each trit in error_hv:
        if random() > lr: set to 0 (mask out)
      Result: only lr fraction of trits survive
    then: Sparse error vector (learning rate controls update magnitude)

  - name: updateRoles
    given: Sparse error HV and current role vectors
    when: |
      For each role r in {Q0,K0,V0, Q1,K1,V1, Q2,K2,V2, FF1, FF2}:
        role[r] = vsa.bundle2(role[r], sparse_error)
    then: All 11 roles updated toward reducing error

  - name: trainOneSample
    given: (context, target) sample and current roles
    when: forward(context) → computeError(output, target) → sparsifyError(lr) → updateRoles
    then: Returns loss (1 - cosineSimilarity(output, target_hv)), roles updated

  - name: trainOneEpoch
    given: Training samples (812) and current learning rate
    when: Shuffle samples, train each sequentially, compute avg train loss
    then: Returns EpochResult with train metrics

  - name: evaluateOnSet
    given: Eval or test samples (102 each) and current roles
    when: Forward pass each sample WITHOUT updating roles, compute loss and accuracy
    then: Returns eval_loss, eval_perplexity, eval_accuracy

  - name: computePhiPerplexity
    given: Set of (output_hv, target) pairs
    when: |
      For each sample:
        similarities = [cosineSimilarity(output, codebook[c]) for c in vocab]
        rank = position of target in sorted similarities (0 = best)
        prob = phi^(-rank / T) / sum(phi^(-k/T) for k in 0..vocab)
      PPL = exp(-avg(log(prob)))
    then: Phi-rank perplexity score

  - name: trainFullWithCurriculum
    given: Max 15 epochs, 4-phase LR schedule, convergence target eval_loss < 0.3
    when: |
      For each epoch:
        lr = schedule_lr(epoch)
        train_result = trainOneEpoch(train_samples, lr)
        eval_result = evaluateOnSet(eval_samples)
        record EpochResult
        check convergence: eval_loss < 0.3 AND stable for 2 epochs
        check early stop: eval_loss increasing for 3 consecutive epochs
        detect anomalies: loss spike, dead role, overfitting, role collapse
    then: Returns TrainingValidation with full loss curve and convergence proof

  - name: measureRoleDrift
    given: Initial role vectors (before training) and current role vectors
    when: For each role: drift = 1 - cosineSimilarity(initial, current)
    then: RoleDriftAnalysis per role (alive if density > 0.3 and drift > 0.01)

  - name: validateConvergenceGuarantee
    given: Training results and v2.25 guarantee (eval_loss < 0.3 within max(16*V, 500) samples)
    when: Check if eval_loss < 0.3 achieved, compare actual vs predicted samples needed
    then: ConvergenceResult with guarantee_met flag

  - name: runFinalTestEval
    given: Trained model and held-out test set (102 samples)
    when: Forward all test samples, compute loss/perplexity/accuracy
    then: Unbiased test metrics (never seen during training)

  - name: generateTrainingReport
    given: TrainingValidation results
    when: Format loss curve table, convergence proof, role analysis, anomaly log
    then: Markdown report documenting empirical training behavior

test_cases:
  - name: loss_decreases
    description: Training loss decreases from epoch 1 to epoch 5
    expected: epoch5.train_loss < epoch1.train_loss

  - name: eval_loss_decreases
    description: Eval loss decreases, proving generalization not memorization
    expected: epoch5.eval_loss < epoch1.eval_loss

  - name: convergence_achieved
    description: Eval loss drops below 0.3 within 15 epochs
    expected: convergence.guarantee_met = true

  - name: perplexity_below_30
    description: Final test perplexity below 30 (vs baseline ~70)
    expected: final_test_perplexity < 30

  - name: roles_alive
    description: All 11 roles have density > 0.3 after training
    expected: all role_analysis entries have is_alive = true

  - name: no_catastrophic_anomalies
    description: No unresolved catastrophic_forgetting or role_collapse
    expected: anomalies list has no unresolved critical entries

  - name: training_under_5_seconds
    description: Full 15-epoch training completes in under 5 seconds
    expected: total_training_time_ms < 5000
